# Project E2E Policy — {{PROJECT_NAME}}

**This file is the single source of truth for how this project is tested.** `/aep-build` and `/aep-wrap`
read it to decide *which tiers gate a layer*, *what environment to dogfood against*, and *when*. It is
**skill-managed** — re-run `/aep-e2e-skill-scaffolding` to revisit it when the project's type or deploy
target changes. No copy lives in `AGENTS.md`: this skill is canonical cross-tool, so Claude Code, Codex,
and Pi all read this same file — that is what keeps behavior consistent across agents.

## The policy (confirmed at scaffold; edit as the project evolves)

| Decision             | This project              |
| -------------------- | ------------------------- |
| **Applicable tiers** | {{E2E_TIERS}}             |
| **Dogfood target**   | {{E2E_TARGET}}            |
| **Journey timing**   | {{E2E_JOURNEY_TIMING}}    |
| **Live policy**      | {{E2E_LIVE_POLICY}}       |

- **Applicable tiers** — only these tiers gate a layer (its `passed` needs them green + every acceptance
  criterion proven). A **CLI** is `1 + 2` (Tier-2 journey is **bash-driven** — run the built binary, assert
  exit code / stdout / fs); a **library** is also `1 + 2` (a bash usage-script `cli` journey exercises its
  public API as a caller would); an API service `1 + 3`; a web/mobile app `1 + 2 (+ 3)`. Only a repo with
  **no runnable surface** (config / schema / docs) is `1`-only — that is the sole `dogfood_target: none`
  case. See the tier table in [`SKILL.md`](./SKILL.md).
- **Dogfood target** — what/where the Tier-2 journeys run against:
  - `cli` — the built **command-line binary**, driven by **bash** (run it as a user would; assert exit
    code / stdout / stderr / filesystem). No URL, no server — pre-merge/local. An agent invoking the CLI
    is the same as a human typing it, so the journey is a faithful dogfood.
  - `local` — against the local dev server (`$BASE_URL` from `.dev-workflow/ports.env`), pre-merge.
  - `deployed:<url>` — against a deployed environment (e.g. a Cloudflare prod/preview URL), typically
    after merge → deploy.
  - `none` — **no runnable surface at all** (pure config / schema / docs repo). Tier-2 is **N/A**; a
    layer's gate is Tier-1 (+ Tier-3) + coverage. No journey, no `journeys/` dir.
- **Journey timing** — governs **only when the journey is EXECUTED**, never when it is authored. The
  journey FILE is **always a pre-merge build deliverable**: `/aep-build` Phase 6 Step A authors it from the
  layer's acceptance criteria and commits it with the feature, regardless of timing. `pre-merge` runs the
  journey in `/aep-build` Phase 6 against `local`; `post-deploy` defers _execution_ to the layer gate
  (after merge → deploy, against the `deployed:<url>` target). With `post-deploy`, a merge sits at
  **`scripted_passed`** until the deployed dogfood flips it to `passed` — that intermediate state honestly
  says "machinery green, product not yet verified". Either way the committed journey already exists; what
  `journey_timing` moves is the run, not the write.

- **Live policy** — which gates spend **cost-bearing dogfood** (live model calls, quota- or fee-metered
  targets): `every_gate` runs the live half at every layer gate; `milestone_gates_only` runs it only at
  the milestone gates named below (all other gates use zero-cost render smokes / scripted tiers, and the
  absent live half is **SKIP**, never FAIL); `none` never spends live runs. Projects with no cost-bearing
  dogfood keep `every_gate` (it is then free). Milestone gates: `{{E2E_MILESTONE_GATES}}`.

## Options reference

```
applicable_tiers : [1] | [1,3] | [1,2] | [1,2,3]          # which tiers gate a layer (project-type driven)
dogfood_target   : none | cli | local | deployed:<url>    # what/where Tier-2 journeys run against (cli = built binary via bash)
journey_timing   : pre-merge | post-deploy                # when the journey half of the gate runs
live_policy      : every_gate | milestone_gates_only | none  # which gates spend cost-bearing (live/quota-metered) dogfood
```

## Sensitive paths (verification hard floor — human-owned)

Globs that force the **`deep` verification tier** (`/aep-gen-eval` → `references/verification-economics.md`)
whenever a story's diff touches them. This list is **human-owned**: the loop never edits it, and no
calibration proposal may loosen it. Confirmed at scaffold (Phase 2) from a stack scan covering auth,
payments, irreversible data operations, migrations, and deploy/CI config — one glob per line:

```yaml
sensitive_paths:
{{E2E_SENSITIVE_PATHS}}
```

> **Referee assets** (test dirs, `journeys/**`, this file, CI workflow definitions) are guarded
> separately: a diff touching them floors at `standard` and a negative assertion delta always forces an
> evaluation round — they never derive the `light` tier.

## Environment preflight probes

Probes run **before any journey/dogfood spend**; an unmet **required** precondition is a named refusal
(`REFUSING [dogfood-secret-absent:<NAME>]`) — `environment` by construction, zero scenarios spent. A gate
probes only the preconditions of criteria it **requires** (derived from `live_policy` — the optional live
half of a non-milestone gate is not probed; its absence stays **SKIP**).

- **Deploy-independent** (run pre-merge in `/aep-build` Phase 6 Step B on every story): required secret
  _names_ present in CI config; expected account fingerprint recorded vs. actual auth identity; env-var
  names wired in deploy config.
- **Target-bound** (run wherever journey execution runs — Phase 6B under `pre-merge`, the `/aep-wrap`
  gate under `post-deploy`): target reachable; deployed bindings present; fixtures seedable.
- **CLI/TUI vocabulary** (when `dogfood_target: cli`): provider auth present; provider reachable; PTY
  driver healthy; fixture repos creatable.

